tip.text:
This gem of a cafe is a welcome addition to Hackney serving up delicious coffee blends in a minimal and airy space adorned with retro stylings. It's just the kind of cafe you'd expect to find in such ends: calm, white walls, full of people doing things on their laptops that are innumerably more important than whatever you are doing on yours.

They pride themselves on their coffee here, so kick things off with a cup of joe, while you decide whether their brunch menu is tempting enough to hang around for. Sourdough bread, slow-roast beans, fried mushrooms and prosciutto topped with poached eggs sure worked on us.

This taqueria has all the spice of a real roadside joint without any of the bowel anxiety. Work your way through a veggie jackfruit taco, topped with crunchy sweet potato; or a taco packed with slow-cooked lamb topped with coriander and onions; and a steak quesadilla perhaps? It's important you know it wouldn't be weird to order one of every taco. No shame; be free, young warrior.

The drinks are just as cray as the colourful decor. Get off on lime, watermelon or cucumber margaritas (with your choice of tequila or mezcal) or try your hand at a 'Michelada', which is basically a beer-based Bloody Mary. Curious aren't you pussy cat?

Ps: It's £2 tacos on Tuesdays. Hells yeah.

It's a well known fact that judging a cafe around this area is partly to do with the quality and value of the food but mainly down to its aesthetic value. Insta is important and you really ought not forget that. Cafe Miami, situated in the beautiful, rather incongruous listed Strand Building brings a nice dose of Art Deco to Clapton, with its pastel hues, retro furnishings and Americana specialities.

The main talking point is probably the interior - plenty of phones come out at this place - and, to be honest, the food is nothing above your usual brunch fare; albeit with some Miami-inspired decadence. Waffle burgers with chorizo, avocado and fried egg; fish finger tacos; and hot honey smoked salmon with ricotta on focaccia all promise plenty of richness and come in around the £9 mark.

That vegan cafe in Bethnal Green everyone is raving about. You've heard of it. We're sure you have. It's 100% vegan, community run and not for profit. Get your vegan samosas, sausage rolls, cakes and milkshakes, or go for a posh coffee.

You can also buy produce to take away, including vegan cheeses, faux meats, tofu, tempeh, Club Mate & Fritz Kola (German drinks), as well as politically-charged vegan cookbooks. Because you never know when you might need one. Hell, you could probably use one right now.

To all those who think vegans don't do it indulgent we present: We Are Vegan Everything. A very Insta friendly, Bali-vibes brunch spot and cafe in Hackney that's doing mighty, naughty things with plant-based food. We came in for brunch and were really damn satisfied by both the sweet (blueberry pancakes and vegan coconut cream) and savoury (sourdough topped with tomatoes, mushrooms and avocado). It feels like the kind of place an Australian wellness influencer in Bali would have created, and we mean that in a nice way. The freakshake, meanwhile, is one of the most rich and decadent shakes we've ever sampled.

This quaint little cafe is not geographically constrained by its Hackney location, and serves up some top notch platters focussing on cuisines from all over. From Latino, Scandinavian, Oriental, Middle Eastern, American... it's pretty much got it all. Oh, and they're all only £7.50. Despite the worldly dishes, they've still got that Hackney community vibe, with convivial seating, regular supper clubs and local artwork plastered on the walls.

If you only feel peckish, the tea here is pretty fuckin' delightful, served in cute tea-sets, pots and saucers, all sourced from local junk shops. Service can be a tad slow, but it's more because they're overwhelmed, and not because they're rude and cba, so we feel mean for even bringing it up.

When you heard the chaps behind the Sebright Arms were opening up a restaurant you were excited, right? So were we. And our instincts were right because The Vincent is a very decent all-day brunch & cocktail spot perfect for doing a bit of indulging, offering a bit of a rarity in these parts: substantial bang for your buck.

In a calming wooden oasis featuring big teak lanterns and banana trees, this is a perfect hangover or lazy weekend affair. The menu spans from the healthy to the downright decadent, with classic breakfast offerings joined by stuff like veggie hash, fried chicken and waffle, and their famous bunsmith buns filled with fried chicken or cheeseburgers. But whatever you do, save some space for their waffle with berries and cream - we got it thinking we only wanted a bite, and before we knew it our plate was licked clean.

listing.name: Dark Arts Coffee / I Will Kill Again
listing.subtitle: Roastery and Cafe

tip.text:
Some sort of enigmatic magic is afoot in a railway arch in Homerton, where an alluring mishmash of the occult, biker culture and insanely good coffee is turning people a little bit crazy - although it could just be that jitter juice. A roastery during the week (Dark Arts Coffee); a vegan-orientated cafe on the weekends (I Will Kill Again), we rate this as a really memorable place to do the coffee and brunch thing in East.

The coffee is dangerously moreish: beans from all over the world that are uniquely blended into something so damn creamy you can almost taste the threat of your own demise. The brunch, meanwhile, is of the quality to have vegans and non-vegans alike rushing down to get into plates that artfully combine smoked tempeh rashers, crispy potato rosti and sweet sun-dried tomatoes to create something greater than the sum of their parts. Throw in a chilled ambience with laid-back, black-clad owners dripping with cool, and you have yourself a spot that walks the walk and talks the talk.

Isreali-inspired Bernstein’s Bar is a slice of Tel-Aviv cool sitting on a corner of Chatsworth Road. This is an ideal place to take a seat (inside or on the pavement) and watch the Clapton cool cats pass whilst tucking into hearty Middle Eastern dishes; having a coffee; doing the lazy lunch dance; or dipping the beak in something strong and letting the evening take over.

Sourcing plenty of their bits locally, the cuisine here is the comforting chow of Israel and the Levant: fish, meat and cheese sharing boards alongside filling and tasty soups - the chicken stew is known to cure almost every illness known to man. Serving all sorts for all sorts, it’s another vibey spot to add to Clapton’s growing arsenal.

We lament the fall of the tram as much as the next app, but that cloud has a silver lining because the old Clapton Tram Depot has been superbly converted into a soothing, beautiful café full of botany, exposed brickwork, ancient beams and parquetry flooring. The owners of this place have really put some time into the aesthetic and we're digging it. They serve breakfast, lunch and also sell a range of organic products from this light-filled space.

Whilst the lunch menu features a couple of toasted sandwiches and a soup of the day, we stopped by for a lazy breakfast where the menu comes with all the classics: Bloody Mary, sourdough, granola, eggs, bacon. Whatever you do, though, get a dish featuring their portobello mushrooms in tarragon and soya cashew cream - you won't regret it. With soft piano music playing overhead, and locals reading the paper and having a chat, this is a green oasis of calm in Clapton.

Don’t fall for the 60s worker’s-cafe exterior - Jim’s is a modern brunching spot through and through, gimmicky warts and all. What some lesser publications might call ‘hipster’, gimmicks come by way of the Black Skulls, the motorcycle ‘lifestyle brand’ that have taken over the residence with leathers on the walls and motorbike parts dotted about. As much as we’d like to sneer, the aesthetic meshes quite well with the retro wood-panelled diner vibe.

From bircher muesli to juicy, pink double cheese burgers, this is an all-day dining affair, but for us it’s gotta be brunch, when classics like kedgeree, salt beef hash, and kippers come into play - all done with the kind of finesse you'd associate with a more formal setting. Wash it down with an expertly crafted bloody mary (read: strong) and you’ve got yourself a breakfast-lunch mash-up fit for a king - or at least the boss of a Hackney biker gang.

Sure you've been in your fair share of cafes, but not one quite like this. Owner Aidan, an avid collector and lover of all things natural history, has lovingly (and painstakingly) created a cafe-cum-miniature-natural-history-museum and it's a transportive, singular experience - as close to the cupboard-into-Narnia flex as it's possible to get. From the luxey pastel pink and creme hues; to the foraged branches and moss; to the surreal taxidermy sitting proud, it's an aesthetic rarity - and a reminder that sometimes fetishes can be a good thing.

With the layout of a small gallery, glass cabinets are filled with all manner of fossils, bones, artefacts and specimens. All for sale; all worthy of a momentary browse. And if that tummy starts to rumble, you'll find coffees, cakes and a short breakfast and lunch menu with carefully put together dishes such as Ottolenghi home-baked beans, salsa and beetroot yoghurt on sourdough; manchego and cheddar toastie with truffle oil; or slow roasted garlic and thyme mushrooms on toast. Keep an eye out for a cute garden out back too.

You might walk past Lardo in London Fields thinking it was just another posh warehouse conversion, but once you spot the glimmering disco ball-like pizza oven hanging from the ceiling, you'll know this is a chiller affair. You'll also know it's Lardo, as there's no signage on the door.

There's a lovely outdoor area if you're there on the one night of the year where it's warm enough to sit outside, or plenty of seating and natural light indoors so you can see that warm, sizzling pizza. They also do pasta and all your classic Italian puds (tiramisu, you know we love you), but we'd recommend starting off the night with a cold Spritz and a charcuterie board. Because, why on earth wouldn't you?

Rawduck lays on some quality all-day dining with fresh seasonal produce at the centre of their breakfast, lunch and dinner menus. We've been known to head there for breakfasts of home-made granolas, oats, and egg dishes with middle eastern bread; comforting pasta lunches and more luxurious dinners.

The drinks are just as exciting here with a rotating list of natural and biodynamic wines and house kombuchas, drinking vinegars and kefirs. Blimey that's a lot of fermenting. Over the summer grab an outdoor bench to nibble your raspberry upside down cake with Iranian pistachios and orange blossom yoghurt. Happy days.

This snug independent cafe is a popular Well Street Market staple - a small, rustic-feeling space with a simple blue and white facade that locals pack into for their rocket-fuel (coffee), breakfast, brunch or lunch.

In the morning it's strictly a baps ting, with bacon, chorizo & avocado or egg & sausage doing the business, sometimes aided by a tasty tomato relish; brunch is the typical fare but slightly more elaborate at the weekends; and then it's ciabattas and soups at lunch. It's not that cheap but the quality of food is high - for an occasional weekend brunch it's a decent shout.

With no website or Facebook page, these guys really have hit peak post-hipster status. The menu is modest (written up on a chalk board, of course) but manages to cover all your fave brekky options - the french toast - topped with berries, bacon, and a shed ton of maple is a must. Wash that down with a freshly-squeezed juice of the day and a Climpson and Sons coffee, and you'll be feeling like a smug bastard in the most wonderful of ways.

If we were the suspicious sorts, we'd begin to suspect there was something a little fishy about E5 and their growing bakery empire. How did they expand so quick? Is that flour really flour? Are they planning on a bread monopoly? But let's put those concerns to one side and enjoy this institution for what it is: a purveyor of delicious organic and natural sourdough bread.

In one arch you'll find the cafe, a busy hub where affluent Hackneyites come in for their routine cup of joe, fresh lunches and cakes and treats. In another arch, you've got their store, which is all about artisan goods at appropriately inflated prices. And then the mill itself, where all that...milling takes place and the dough transforms into truly delicious bread. Look out for their bread and pizza making classes too, which are super popular.

To the north of London Fields sits Footnote, a family-run neighbourhood  brunch spot with a focus on the healthy. The prices are a little high, but plenty of love and attention is put into the food from the friendly staff. The venue itself is light, visually pleasing and pretty charming in its own way. Expect to see people chewing the fat over a coffee and some eggs, but don't come here expecting to set up shop with your lappy - the focus is on conversation, not procrastination.

OK we've seen the look on your face. How can a pub be 100% vegan, you're wondering. Well it pretty much means that, wherever possible, all the trimmings (food, drinks, fixtures and fittings) are plant-based and sustainably sourced.

Food is seen to by Club Mexicana which means tacos, nachos and burritos piled high with guacamole, tomatillo salsa, sour cream, pink onions, pickled chillies, chimichurri, fresh lime and coriander. Sounds tingly and tasty right? Our fave was the tofish sandwich which went down a treat. Wash all that down with cask ales (without the fish bits), Beavertown beer, small batch wines and some tasty cocky Ts.

We also popped by for brunch and devoured some tangy, spicy chick'n waffles with chilli maple and bacon (as decadent as it sounds); a full Mexican breakfast with all the plant-based trimmings; some fried tortillas with cherries and cream; and more cocktails that we'd care to admit. It's very on trend, for sure, but it's got the flavour chops to back itself.

Kitchen closed on Mondays.

No way are the vegan wizards behind The Brook about to sacrifice flavour in their pursuit of plant-based pleasure - this is as close to vegan junk food as we've found in London. It's a vegan tapas restaurant and cocktail bar; a suitably laid-back, friendly and DIY-chic space where vegans and curious non-vegans enter the doors to see what's next in the vegolution. The answer: pretty nice grub with a surprising and satisfying indulgence about it.

The tip is to share five or six of their tapas dishes between two - and let us point you towards the moreish sesame chick'n skewers; the bountiful and comforting jackfruit quesadillas; and a zingy lime and coconut dal. Portion sizes are not huge - and potentially a pound or two over what we'd like - but given the meticulous R&D and care gone into creating each dish, we're prepared to make allowances.

The cocktails here are also not a simple add-on. Their huge choice of converted classics and house specials are put on the same footing as the food - meaning that whilst hungry foodies frequent the front and tuck into the tasty bits, the bar area and tables at the back create an altogether looser vibe.
